  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="red" WIDTH="150"><B>Conclusion</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">The controlling factor which we have<BR ALIGN='left'/>concluded brings this case within the<BR ALIGN='left'/>statute is that a basic element of the<BR ALIGN='left'/>plan was the continuance of the chemical<BR ALIGN='left'/>manufacturing business in the corporate<BR ALIGN='left'/>shell of the new company, with the gain<BR ALIGN='left'/>(were it not for the &quot;boot&quot;) not having<BR ALIGN='left'/>sufficiently crystallized for<BR ALIGN='left'/>recognition, because the collective<BR ALIGN='left'/>interests of the shareholders &quot;still<BR ALIGN='left'/>remained in solution.&quot;</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
>]
	"5DX66K2KDn" [label=<
<TABLE BORDER="0" CELLBORDER="1" CELLSPACING="0" CELLPADDING="4">
  <TR><TD BGCOLOR="lightblue" WIDTH="150"><B>Analysis</B></TD></TR>
  <TR><TD ALIGN="left" WIDTH="150">What is controlling is that in both the<BR ALIGN='left'/>&quot;popular and economic sense,&quot;[5] and the<BR ALIGN='left'/>intendment of the statute,<BR ALIGN='left'/>considerations of &quot;boot&quot; aside,[6] gain<BR ALIGN='left'/>or loss is not sufficiently crystallized<BR ALIGN='left'/>for recognition by the mere transfer of<BR ALIGN='left'/>a going business to another corporation<BR ALIGN='left'/>for operation indefinitely; &quot;the<BR ALIGN='left'/>collective interests still remained in<BR ALIGN='left'/>solution.&quot; Helvering v. Gregory, 2 Cir.,<BR ALIGN='left'/>1934, 69 F.2d 809, 811. Hence, the<BR ALIGN='left'/>transaction was within the statute.</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
>]
